{
  "text": "Functional MSCs were initially identified by their capacity to form clonogenic cell clusters in vitro, a common feature different to other stromal cell populations. In the current study, self-renewal potential was measured in a CFU-F assay and sphere formation assay. As indicated in Figs. 3A and B, the CFU-F frequency remained relatively higher in SCB-MSCs than in BMS-MSCs (SCB-MSCs versus BMS-MSCs: 6.33 \u00b1 0.94 versus 3 \u00b1 0.82, 11 \u00b1 1.63 versus 5.67 \u00b1 0.94, 17 \u00b1 0.82 versus 10.67 \u00b1 1.25 for days 5, 10, and 15, respectively. Sphere formation assays have long been used to evaluate progenitor/multipotent cell populations in epithelial systems. Recent studies suggested that MSCs can also produce spheres [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Three days after culture on ultra-low adherent tissue culture plates, sphere formation was evident in the SCB-MSC group and BMS-MSC group (Fig. 3C) . These spheres were disassociated and re-plated on non-adherent plates. Fewer spheres developed after another 3 days of culture. Interestingly, there was a noticeable difference in primary and secondary sphere number in SCB-MSC culture compared with to in BMS culture (SCB-MSCs versus BMS-MSCs: 38 \u00b1 9.53 versus 22 \u00b1 0.82, 24.67 \u00b1 3.21 versus 10 \u00b1 1.63 for primary spheres and secondary spheres, respectively. Fig. 3D , *P<0.05; **P<0.01).",
  "correct_citation": {
